        "name": "contentManager_writeContent",
        "arguments": "{\"sessionId\":\"doc_sprint_2024-10-26_09:17\",\"workspaceId\":\"documentation-project-alpha\",\"path\":\"/docs/tutorials/grpc-load-balancer.md\",\"content\":\"---\\ntitle: \\\"Configuring a gRPC Load Balancer on Kubernetes\\\"\\ndescription: \\\"Step‑by‑step guide for DevOps engineers to set up and tune a gRPC load balancer in a Kubernetes environment.\\\"\\ntags:\\n  - devops\\n  - kubernetes\\n  - grpc\\n  - load-balancer\\n  - tutorial\\naliases:\\n  - \\\"gRPC LB Setup\\\"\\n  - \\\"K8s gRPC Load Balancer\\\"\\ncategory: \\\"documentation\\\"\\n---\\n\\n# Introduction\\n\\n> [!note] This tutorial assumes you are familiar with basic Kubernetes concepts, Helm, and have a cluster you can modify.\\n\\nConfiguring a gRPC load balancer in Kubernetes often involves deploying a proxy such as **Envoy** or **NGINX** that understands HTTP/2 and can perform advanced routing. We will walk through a complete setup using Envoy, covering deployment, service definition, and validation.\\n\\n## Prerequisites\\n\\n- A running Kubernetes cluster (v1.22+ recommended)\\n- `kubectl` configured for the cluster\\n- Helm 3 installed\\n- Basic knowledge of gRPC services\\n- Access to a container registry for custom images (optional)\\n\\n- [ ] Verify cluster access: `kubectl get nodes`\\n- [ ] Install Helm if not present: `curl https://raw.githubusercontent.com/helm/helm/master/scripts/get-helm-3 | bash`\\n\\n## 1. Deploy Envoy as a gRPC Load Balancer\\n\\nWe will use the official Envoy Helm chart. This chart creates a Deployment, Service, and ConfigMap for you.\\n\\n```bash\\nhelm repo add envoyproxy https://helm.envoyproxy.io\\nhelm repo update\\nhelm install grpc-envoy envoyproxy/envoy \\\n  --set service.type=LoadBalancer \\\n  --set envoy.extraArgs=\\\"--config-path /etc/envoy/envoy.yaml\\\"\\n```\\n\\nThe Service is exposed via a LoadBalancer (or NodePort in on‑prem environments).\\n\\n### Envoy Configuration\\nCreate a ConfigMap with the Envoy listener and cluster configuration that routes gRPC traffic. Save the following as `envoy-config.yaml`.\\n\\n```yaml\\napiVersion: v1\\nkind: ConfigMap\\nmetadata:\\n  name: envoy-config\\n  namespace: default\\ndata:\\n  envoy.yaml: |\\n    static_resources:\\n      listeners:\\n      - name: listener_grpc\\n        address:\\n          socket_address:\\n            address: 0.0.0.0\\n            port_value: 50051\\n        filter_chains:\\n        - filters:\\n          - name: envoy.filters.network.http_connection_manager\\n            typed_config:\\n              \"@type\": type.googleapis.com/envoy.extensions.filters.network.http_connection_manager.v3.HttpConnectionManager\\n              stat_prefix: ingress_http\\n              codec_type: AUTO\\n              route_config:\\n                name: local_route\\n                virtual_hosts:\\n                - name: grpc_service\\n                  domains: [\"*\"]\\n                  routes:\\n                  - match:\\n                      prefix: \"/\"\\n                    route:\\n                      cluster: grpc_backend\\n              http_filters:\\n              - name: envoy.filters.http.router\\n      clusters:\\n      - name: grpc_backend\\n        connect_timeout: 0.25s\\n        type: STRICT_DNS\\n        lb_policy: ROUND_ROBIN\\n        load_assignment:\\n          cluster_name: grpc_backend\\n          endpoints:\\n          - lb_endpoints:\\n            - endpoint:\\n                address:\\n                  socket_address:\\n                    address: grpc-backend.default.svc.cluster.local\\n                    port_value: 50051\\n```\\n\\nApply the ConfigMap:\\n\\n```bash\\nkubectl apply -f envoy-config.yaml\\n```\\n\\n## 2. Deploy a Sample gRPC Service\\n\\nFor demonstration we will deploy a simple gRPC echo service. The image `grpc-ecosystem/greeter` is publicly available.\\n\\n```bash\\nkubectl apply -f - <<EOF\\napiVersion: apps/v1\\nkind: Deployment\\nmetadata:\\n  name: grpc-backend\\nspec:\\n  replicas: 2\\n  selector:\\n    matchLabels:\\n      app: grpc-backend\\n  template:\\n    metadata:\\n      labels:\\n        app: grpc-backend\\n    spec:\\n      containers:\\n      - name: grpc-backend\\n        image: grpc-ecosystem/greeter\\n        ports:\\n        - containerPort: 50051\\n---\\napiVersion: v1\\nkind: Service\\nmetadata:\\n  name: grpc-backend\\nspec:\\n  selector:\\n    app: grpc-backend\\n  ports:\\n  - protocol: TCP\\n    port: 50051\\n    targetPort: 50051\\nEOF\\n```\\n\\n## 3. Validate the Load Balancer\\n\\nWith the Envoy service exposed, you can test the gRPC endpoint from any client that supports HTTP/2. Below is an example using `grpcurl`.\\n\\n```bash\\ngrpcurl -plaintext $(kubectl get svc grpc-envoy -o jsonpath='{.status.loadBalancer.ingress[0].ip}'):50051

